# 06_video_device.patch   (ported; AG Projects custom macOS video backend)
#
# Introduces the framebuffer renderer (fb_dev.c) and, on macOS, our own
# AVFoundation capture backend avf_dev.m - which REPLACES upstream's
# darwin_dev.m/metal_dev.m on Darwin (see 40_videodev_extra_objs.patch for
# the build wiring).
#
# Fix note (June 2026) - avf_factory_refresh() crash + UAF
# --------------------------------------------------------
# The avf_dev.m this patch creates originally contained three defects of
# our own making (not upstream); they are fixed inline here, so the
# interim stand-alone patches 50_avf_dev_refresh_overflow and
# 51_avf_dev_device_retain_uaf are no longer needed and have been removed:
#
#   1. Heap buffer overflow in avf_factory_refresh(). The device list was
#      counted and filled in two passes over [AVCaptureDevice devices]
#      using the live -isSuspended predicate; a camera becoming usable
#      between the passes (Continuity Camera, USB hot-plug, wake) let the
#      fill pass write past the dev_pool allocation -> crash inside
#      pjmedia_vid_dev_refresh() (folded symbol; static fn) on the
#      PJSIPUA.refresh_video_devices() worker thread. Now sized by the
#      array length with a hard bound guard.
#   2. NULL deref: pj_ansi_strncpy(..., [device.localizedName UTF8String])
#      crashed when localizedName was transiently nil. Now falls back to
#      "Unknown camera".
#   3. Use-after-free: di->dev stored an unretained AVCaptureDevice from
#      the autoreleased device array (drained by [apool release]); later
#      reused in init_avf_stream(). Now [device retain]ed, balanced by
#      release loops in refresh() and factory_destroy() (avf_dev.m is MRC).
#
